# SmartTools Bot (@SmartTools333Bot)

A Telegram bot with a menu of tools. Currently includes:
- Word Counter

Built with error handling so it won't crash on a bad message or a dropped
connection ‚Äî errors are logged and the bot keeps running.

## Step 1 ‚Äî Get your bot token
1. Open Telegram, search for **@BotFather**
2. If you haven't registered `@SmartTools333Bot` yet, send `/newbot` and follow the prompts
3. BotFather gives you a token that looks like `123456789:AAExampleTokenHere`
4. Copy it ‚Äî you'll paste it into Railway in Step 3 (never paste it into code or GitHub)

## Step 2 ‚Äî Push this code to GitHub
In this folder, run:
```bash
git init
git add .
git commit -m "SmartTools bot - word counter"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/smarttools-bot.git
git push -u origin main
```
Replace `YOUR_USERNAME` with your GitHub username. Create the empty repo on
GitHub first if you haven't already (github.com ‚Üí New repository).

## Step 3 ‚Äî Deploy on Railway
1. Go to https://railway.app and log in with GitHub
2. Click **New Project ‚Üí Deploy from GitHub repo**
3. Select your `smarttools-bot` repo
4. Click on the deployed service ‚Üí **Variables** tab ‚Üí **New Variable**
   - Name: `BOT_TOKEN`
   - Value: (paste the token from Step 1)
5. Railway reads the `Procfile` and runs `python bot.py` automatically
6. Check the **Deployments ‚Üí View Logs** tab ‚Äî you should see:
   `Bot starting with polling...`
   If you see that line with no errors below it, it's live.

## Step 4 ‚Äî Test it
Open Telegram, go to `@SmartTools333Bot`, send `/start`. You should get the
menu with the Word Counter button.

## Common mistakes to avoid
- Don't put your token directly in `bot.py` ‚Äî always use the Railway
  `BOT_TOKEN` variable. If the token leaks (e.g. pushed to GitHub), revoke it
  in BotFather with `/revoke` and generate a new one.
- Only run **one instance** of the bot at a time (don't also run it locally
  while it's live on Railway) ‚Äî Telegram will throw a "Conflict" error if two
  processes poll with the same token simultaneously.
- Make sure the repo's root contains `bot.py`, `requirements.txt`, and
  `Procfile` directly (not nested inside a subfolder), or Railway won't find
  them.

## Adding more tools later
1. Add a new button in `main_menu_keyboard()` in `bot.py`
2. Add a matching `if query.data == "your_tool":` block in `button_handler()`
3. Add handling logic in `handle_text()` (or a new handler for images/files)
4. Commit and push to GitHub ‚Äî Railway auto-redeploys on every push
